# Mobile Application Patterns

**Capability test:** Skip this file unless the task targets a mobile app codebase (native or cross-platform).

Coding patterns specific to mobile app development. These extend the universal rules (naming, auth, API, testing, etc.) with mobile-specific concerns. IF you're building a mobile app, apply these patterns.

All numeric values (launch times, memory thresholds, list sizes) in this file are `[DEFAULT]` - adjust per project and target devices.

---

## Platform Coverage

These rules apply to:
- **React Native** (JavaScript/TypeScript)
- **Flutter** (Dart)
- **SwiftUI / UIKit** (iOS native)
- **Jetpack Compose / XML** (Android native)
- **Kotlin Multiplatform** (KMP)
- **Any cross-platform framework**

The principles are the same. Implementation adapts to the framework.

---

## Navigation

### Structure Pattern

```
App Entry
  ├── Initial Screen (determine app state)
  │   ├── State A -> Navigator A (stack)
  │   └── State B -> Navigator B (stack)
  │
  └── Main Navigator (tabs or drawer)
      ├── Tab 1: Primary feature (stack)
      ├── Tab 2: Secondary feature (stack)
      ├── Tab 3-5: Additional features (stack each)
```

### Rules

- **Tab bar** for 3-5 main sections (mobile standard) - bottom tabs are most common, but choose the navigation pattern that fits your app's information architecture
- **Drawer** for 6+ sections (less discoverable, use if necessary)
- **Stack navigation** within each tab (push/pop, with back button)
- **Active tab indicator** clearly visible (color + icon state change)
- **Badge on tab icon** for pending item counts (if applicable to your feature)
- **Deep linking** for every screen that makes sense to share/bookmark
- **Back button** behavior: Android hardware back works correctly; iOS swipe-back gesture works
- **Modal presentation** for creation flows, filters, and actions that break the current context
- **Never lose scroll position** when navigating back to a tab

---

## Screen Structure

Every screen follows this template:

```
Screen Component
  ├── Loading state (skeleton or spinner - shown first)
  ├── Error state (retry button - shown on failure)
  ├── Empty state (illustration + copy - shown when no data)
  └── Content state (actual UI - shown when data loaded)
```

**Rules:**
- **Safe area handling**: Content respects notch, status bar, home indicator on all devices
- **Keyboard avoidance**: Form fields scroll into view when keyboard opens; keyboard never covers inputs
- **Pull-to-refresh** on data-fetching list screens (skip for real-time features with live connections, maps, and read-only archives)
- **Infinite scroll or pagination** for lists (never load all records at once)
- **Scroll to top** on tab bar tap (when already on that tab)

